Relay-style cursor pagination is the standard for GraphQL. The key: encode cursor as opaque string, decode on server.

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

function encodeCursor(id: string, createdAt: Date): string {
  return Buffer.from(JSON.stringify({ id, t: createdAt.toISOString() })).toString('base64url');
}

function decodeCursor(cursor: string): { id: string; t: string } {
  return JSON.parse(Buffer.from(cursor, 'base64url').toString());
}

async function getConnection(first: number, after?: string) {
  let where;
  if (after) {
    const { t } = decodeCursor(after);
    where = lt(nodes.createdAt, new Date(t));
  }

  const items = await db.select().from(nodes)
    .where(where)
    .orderBy(desc(nodes.createdAt))
    .limit(first + 1);

  const hasNextPage = items.length > first;
  const edges = items.slice(0, first).map(node => ({
    cursor: encodeCursor(node.id, node.createdAt),
    node,
  }));

  return {
    edges,
    pageInfo: {
      hasNextPage,
      endCursor: edges[edges.length - 1]?.cursor ?? null,
    },
  };
}
```

Drizzle transactions default to READ COMMITTED isolation. This means:

```typescript
await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  const [node] = await tx.select().from(nodes).where(eq(nodes.id, id));
  // Another request updates the same node here
  const [sameNode] = await tx.select().from(nodes).where(eq(nodes.id, id));
  // sameNode may have different data than node!
});
```

For operations that need consistent reads within a transaction, use REPEATABLE READ:

```typescript
await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  // All reads see the same snapshot
  const [node] = await tx.select().from(nodes).where(eq(nodes.id, id));
  // ...
}, { isolationLevel: 'repeatable read' });
```

But beware: REPEATABLE READ can throw serialization errors that you must catch and retry. SERIALIZABLE is even stricter and requires more retries.

```typescript
// Branded type prevents mixing up different ID types
type Brand<T, B extends string> = T & { readonly __brand: B };

type UserId = Brand<string, 'UserId'>;
type NodeId = Brand<string, 'NodeId'>;
type AgentId = Brand<string, 'AgentId'>;

// Constructor functions
const UserId = (id: string) => id as UserId;
const NodeId = (id: string) => id as NodeId;
const AgentId = (id: string) => id as AgentId;

// Now TypeScript catches mix-ups:
function getNode(id: NodeId): Node { /* ... */ }
function getUser(id: UserId): User { /* ... */ }

const userId = UserId('abc-123');
const nodeId = NodeId('def-456');

getNode(nodeId);  // OK
getNode(userId);  // ERROR: Type 'UserId' is not assignable to 'NodeId'
```

Zero runtime overhead — brands are erased during compilation. Use this for any string/number type that shouldn't be interchangeable.
